{{Infobox comedian|name=Duncan "Chase Me" Norvelle|image=|image_size=|caption=|birth_name=Duncan Norvelle|birth_date=|birth_place=[[Leicestershire]], England|medium=[[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], television|nationality=British|active=|genre=|influences=|influenced=|website=|partner=Lynn Trevallion}}'''Duncan Norvelle''' (born 1958, [[Hoton]], [[Loughborough]], Leicestershire, England) is an English [[comedian]] in the [[Variety show|variety]] tradition, who appeared on television from the early 1980s. He is probably most famous for his catch phrase "Chase me!", leading to his often being referred to as Duncan "Chase me" Norvelle.<ref name="star" /> His act was based on appearing to be a stereotypical [[Camp (style) |camp]] [[homosexual]], whereas Norvelle is heterosexual. He has three children.<ref name="Daily Record">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/BARRYMORE'S+WIFE+FALLS+FOR+ANOTHER+CAMP+COMIC.-a060560256 |title=Barrymore's Wife Falls For Another Camp Comic |website=Thefreelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> Duncan worked at Courtaulds Hosiery before becoming a comedian in Shepshed Leicestershire. He also used to frequently visit the Brush club, Loughborough.He also had 3 children jack Yasmine and Sophie.
==Entertainment career== In 1984<ref name="BFI">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/533997/ |title=BFI Screenonline: Blind Date (1985-2003) |website=Screenonline.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> or early 1985<ref name="Independent">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/granadas-hot-new-date-it-started-30-years-ago-as-one-mans-tentative-idea-today-as-blind-date-it-is-one-of-the-most-valuable-properties-in-british-television--and-like-it-or-not-a-part-of-our-national-heritage-1427314.html|title= Independent on Sunday, 6 March 1994 | work=The Independent | location=London | first=Luke | last=Jennings | date=6 March 1994 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> (sources vary), he hosted an unscreened pilot dating show called "It's a Hoot"<ref name="BFI"/> for [[London Weekend Television]]. It was reported that both [[John Birt]], LWT's Director of Programmes and the [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]] regulatory body had reservations about Norvelle's camp style in a dating show; the series was eventually re-titled ''[[Blind Date (UK TV series)|Blind Date]]'' and hosted by [[Cilla Black]].<ref name="Independent"/> 2008 saw him go out on tour as part of the [[Ricky Tomlinson]] Laughter Show.<ref name=star>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/barnsley/Ricky-Tomlinson-meets-Scargill-at.3849351.jp |title=Ricky Tomlinson meets Scargill at opening - GALLERY |publisher=The Star |date=2008-03-06 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> Norvelle spent the 2009 [[pantomime]] season playing [[Buttons (pantomime) |Buttons]] in ''[[Cinderella#Pantomime |Cinderella]]'' in [[Doncaster]], South Yorkshire.
In December 2011, he appeared on ''[[Come Dine with Me#Series 24: Primetime |Celebrity Come Dine with Me]]'' with [[Sean Hughes (comedian) |Sean Hughes]], [[Gina Yashere]] and [[Paul Tonkinson]].
==Health== Norvelle was hospitalised during the first week in April 2012 after suffering a [[stroke]], leaving him [[paralysed]] down the left side of his body.<ref name="BBC News">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18455361| title= BBC News - Comedian Duncan Norvelle suffers stroke|website=BBC | date=15 June 2012 | accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> After nine weeks in hospital, he cancelled his summer season with comedy duo [[Cannon and Ball]], to be replaced by [[Stu Francis]].<ref name="BBC News" />
Since August 2015 Norvelle has been back performing all over the country, choosing the Embassy Theatre, [[Skegness]] as his first performance after over three years off stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonstandard.co.uk/news/comedian-returns-to-stage-at-skegness-following-life-changing-illness-1-6887082|title=Comedian returns to stage at Skegness following life changing illness|work=Boston Standard}}</ref>
==DVDs== Norvelle had an ''In The Club'' DVD released in January 2006 by Boulevard Entertainment; and also appears on the ''Ricky Tomlinson Laughter Show Live'' DVD. The latter included a brief interview.
